{
    "analysis": "We have the file-level summaries from the previous Executor run. Metric data is large (319,703 rows) with 1,368 unique KPI names; top cmdb_ids include many service pods (adservice, frontend-*, checkoutservice-*, productcatalogservice-*, etc.). The top KPI names list reveals many container.node-6.* metrics (network, memory, fs) which suggests node-6 related metrics may be important. Trace data (33,696 rows) covers exactly the incident timeframe (2022-03-20 17:00 to 17:29 CST) and is concentrated on frontend and checkoutservice pods. Logs are sparse (1,826 rows) with only two normalized log names.\n\nWhat we should do next is perform the preprocessing step required by the workflow: calculate global thresholds for component-KPI time series (using the full available series) so we can detect anomalies inside the incident window. To keep the output compact and focused, we should first compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) and basic aggregates (count, mean, max) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair for the most active components (top cmdb_ids by row count). This will allow us to prioritize which component-KPI series to examine for anomalies during 17:00–17:30.\n\nThis is not the final answer yet — we need the threshold table to perform anomaly detection and then inspect candidate series in the incident window.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global aggregates for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair restricted to the top 30 cmdb_id values by total row count (use the full available time range for threshold calculation). For each pair, calculate: count of points, mean(value), max(value), P95(value), and P5(value). Return a compact table limited to the top 50 rows sorted by count (highest first). Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, max, p95, p5. Do not print raw time series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds (count, mean, max, p95, p5) for (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs restricted to the top 30 components by row count and saved the result as agg_top50 in kernel state. The agg_top50 table shows per-pair global P95/P5 thresholds computed from full-series data (as required). Notable observations: many high-count series (61 points) covering the interval, presence of many adservice KPIs and container.node-6.* KPIs, and some sentinel values (-1.0) in GC metrics. Next, we must detect anomalies inside the incident window (March 20, 2022 17:00–17:30 CST) by comparing metric points in that window against these global thresholds to find candidate faulty component-KPI series and earliest anomaly times.\n\nWhat will be done next: scan agg_top50 pairs for actual metric points within the 17:00–17:30 incident window that breach their global thresholds (value > p95 => 'high' anomaly; value < p5 => 'low' anomaly). For each pair that has anomalies, return compact summary: cmdb_id, kpi_name, earliest anomaly timestamp, number of anomaly points in window, anomaly direction ('high' or 'low'), and a simple severity metric (for 'high': max(value)/p95; for 'low': p5/min(value)). Limit output to top 20 pairs sorted by number of anomaly points (descending).",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Using the existing agg_top50 in the kernel and the full metric.csv file, find anomalies within the incident window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 CST (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in agg_top50, filter metric.csv to points in that time window and detect points where value > p95 (use agg_top50.p95) or value < p5 (use agg_top50.p5). For each pair that has at least one anomaly point, compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_count_in_window, direction ('high' or 'low' — if both occur choose the one with more points), and severity (if high: max(value)/p95; if low: p5/min(value)). Return top 20 pairs sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc. Provide results as a list of dicts; do not print raw time series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor result (anomaly_list) we already detected many metric anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-20 17:00–17:30 CST). Top anomalies include adservice.app.grpc.mrt starting at 17:00 with 5 high points, and a cluster of shippingservice-0 container.node-6.* anomalies starting between 17:04–17:28 (notably a large spike on container_network_receive_MB at 17:07 with high severity ~7.72). These patterns suggest at least two distinct problem times: one near 17:00 affecting adservice RPC metrics, and another starting ~17:07 affecting shippingservice-0 network/memory/node metrics (with subsequent events at 17:27–17:28). To localize the two failures we should (A) collapse anomalies from KPI-level to component-level to find which components have multiple KPI faults and their earliest fault times, and (B) use traces and logs around those component-first-anomaly times to verify propagation and identify the most downstream faulty component in traces and the underlying resource reason.\n\nNext, we must create a compact per-component anomaly summary (aggregating the per-KPI anomaly_list) to prioritize components that show multi-KPI faults and earliest occurrence times. This will identify candidate components for the two failures so we can then query traces/logs focused on those times/components.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Aggregate the existing anomaly_list (in kernel state) by cmdb_id. For each cmdb_id compute: earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum of earliest_anomaly_timestamp across its KPI pairs), total_kpi_pairs_with_anomaly (number of distinct kpi_name with anomalies), total_anomaly_points (sum of anomaly_count_in_window across its KPI pairs), max_severity (maximum severity across its KPI pairs), and dominant_direction (the direction with the highest count among that component's KPI pairs: 'high' or 'low'). Return the top 20 components sorted by total_anomaly_points descending as a list of dicts with those fields. Do not print raw metric series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies and produced a component-level summary: shippingservice-0 and adservice are the top anomalous components during 2022-03-20 17:00–17:30 CST. shippingservice-0 shows many KPI anomalies (9 KPI pairs, 24 anomaly points) with a very large severity spike on container_network_receive_MB at 17:07 (severity ~7.72). adservice shows multiple RPC metric anomalies starting at 17:00 (app.grpc.mrt high starting 17:00; app.grpc.count high starting 17:15). According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to see whether those metric anomalies correspond to increased latency/error traces and to find which faulty service is most downstream in call chains. Traces will also help determine whether shippingservice-0 or adservice is upstream/downstream and which event likely caused each failure. Therefore we should compute compact aggregates for trace metrics per (cmdb_id, trace_name) to spot large duration/error spikes and earliest timestamps of those spikes.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Using trace.csv, aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) over the full available trace data. For each group compute: count, mean(value), max(value), P95(value), P5(value), and the timestamp when the max(value) first occurred (earliest_timestamp_of_max). Return the top 20 groups sorted by max(value) descending, with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, mean, max, p95, p5, earliest_timestamp_of_max. Keep output compact (max 20 rows)." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated trace groups across the full trace dataset and obtained per-(cmdb_id,trace_name) stats including P95/P5 and the timestamp of the observed maximum. The top peaks are concentrated on frontend pods (large row_count peaks around 17:11) and several downstream services (productcatalogservice2-0, cartservice2-0, recommendationservice2-0, adservice2-0). From metric analysis we already have two primary candidate components with metric faults during the incident window: shippingservice-0 (many container.node-6.* KPI anomalies with earliest anomaly at 17:00 and a severe network receive MB spike at 17:07) and adservice (RPC metrics anomalous starting 17:00 and 17:15). According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is targeted trace analysis to determine whether these metric anomalies correspond to trace-level latency or error spikes and to identify the most-downstream faulty service in call chains. We should therefore detect trace anomalies (duration, error_rate, row_count) within 17:00–17:30 for traces related to shippingservice-0, adservice, and related frontends so we can link metric faults to trace propagation and establish which failure corresponds to which root cause.\n\nThis is not final yet — we need the trace-anomaly table to localize each failure to a component/time/reason.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the previously computed per-group thresholds (use full-series P95 and P5), detect trace anomalies in the incident window 2022-03-20 17:00:00 to 2022-03-20 17:30:00 CST. Restrict to trace_name values that contain any of these substrings: 'duration', 'error_rate', 'row_count'. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group that has anomalies in the window, compute: cmdb_id, trace_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp in window breaching threshold), anomaly_count_in_window, direction ('high' if value>p95, 'low' if value<p5; if both, choose the direction with more points), and severity (if high: max(value)/p95; if low: p5/min(value)). Return up to the top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count_in_window descending as a list of dicts. Do not return raw time series." 
}

